<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-07-22T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-07-22T14:00:00-05:00" n="696" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d696">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/4322</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-07-22T19:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 22, 1915, 7 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 7.35 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2511. Your 1852, July 15.<note n="1" xml:id="d696fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_472">p.
                                    472</ref>.</note>
                                <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName> has reminded
                                me that no court has yet passed on the validity of the order in
                                council of March 11, and he intimated that, the prize court in the
                                case of the <hi rend="italic">Neches</hi> would probably have to
                                pass on this question. The foregoing was an incidental part of a
                                general conversation on the validity of the order in council. He
                                promises an early reply to your 1852.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>